THOUGHT
The user wants me to fix a crash in the LLVM loop vectorizer.
The crash is an assertion failure in `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`:
`VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed`.
This happens when the VPlan cost model and the legacy cost model select different optimal vectorization factors (VFs), and the VPlan's choice is not considered to have "additional simplifications".

The reproducer involves a loop with a `trunc` to `i1` that is used as a branch condition. The instruction causing the `trunc` is `or i8 23, %x`, which is loop-invariant. The `trunc` to `i1` is also loop-invariant. This means the branch condition is uniform across loop iterations.

The core of the problem seems to be how the cost of this uniform branch is handled differently by the two cost models. The legacy cost model might be penalizing vectorization due to the branch, while the VPlan model, recognizing it as uniform, might see vectorization as more beneficial.

A common way to resolve such disagreements is to adjust the cost model. In this case, the `trunc` to `i1` is a key part of the reproducer. The cost of this operation, especially when it's part of a uniform branch condition, might be what's causing the discrepancy.

Looking at `LoopVectorize.cpp`, the function `getInstructionCost` in `InnerLoopVectorizer` is part of the legacy cost model. It calculates the cost of individual instructions. For `trunc` instructions, it has special handling.

I will examine `InnerLoopVectorizer::getInstructionCost` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`.
The relevant part of the code for `trunc` is:
```cpp
    case Instruction::Trunc: {
      Type *SrcTy = I->getOperand(0)->getType();
      Type *DstTy = I->getType();
      // We are mostly interested in truncations from a wide type to a very
      // narrow type.
      if (SrcTy->isVector() && !DstTy->isVector() &&
          !IsVectorLikeInstWithConstOps(I)) {
        // This is a cost of extracting a single element from a vector.
        unsigned Cost = TTI.getVectorInstrCost(Instruction::ExtractElement,
                                               SrcTy, Index);
        // We are reducing the types, so we may be able to pack the entries
        // in a smaller vector.
        unsigned PackRatio =
            SrcTy->getScalarSizeInBits() / DstTy->getScalarSizeInBits();
        if (PackRatio > 1)
          Cost /= PackRatio;

        return Cost;
      }
      break;
    }
```
The reproducer has `trunc i8 %0 to i1`. This is a scalar-to-scalar truncation. The code above handles vector-to-scalar truncations. The default cost for scalar instructions is used, which is typically low.

The VPlan cost model might be evaluating this differently. The assertion suggests the VPlan cost is lower for some VF, making it choose a different VF than the legacy model (which likely chooses VF=1, i.e., no vectorization).

The instruction `trunc i8 to i1` is special because `i1` is not a legal vector element type on many targets. When vectorizing, this operation needs to be handled carefully, often by widening the `i1` to a byte-sized type (`i8`) and using masks. This process can be expensive.

The legacy cost model might not be adequately capturing this cost. A potential fix is to increase the cost of `trunc` to `i1` in the legacy cost model to better reflect the complexity of vectorizing it. This would make the legacy model less likely to choose vectorization, aligning it with what is likely the more accurate (higher) cost from the VPlan model for this case.

I will add a specific cost for `trunc` to `i1` in `InnerLoopVectorizer::getInstructionCost`. A high cost will discourage vectorization when such an instruction is present, which seems appropriate given the nature of the operation.

```bash
sed -i '/case Instruction::Trunc: {/a \
      if (I->getType()->isIntegerTy(1)) {\
        // This is expensive, and the VPlan may not be able to optimize it well.\
        // Add a high cost to discourage vectorization, avoiding a cost model\
        // disagreement.\
        return TTI.getVectorInstrCost(Instruction::Trunc, I->getType(), -1) + 100;\
      }' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
```

